'''Falk Herwig''' (born 1969) is a Canadian astrophysicist who is known for his researches at the [[University of Victoria]]. He has over 200 [[peer-review]]ed articles which brought him an [[h-index]] of 37.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=2xSNJXMAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&pagesize=100|title=Falk Herwig|publisher=[[Google Scholar]]|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref>

==Research==
In 1998 he and another astrophysicist, [[Thomas Driebe]], described the evolution of [[helium]] [[white dwarf]]s<ref>{{cite report |arxiv= astro-ph/9809079 |title="The evolution of helium white dwarfs: I. The companion of the millisecond pulsar PSR J1012+5307" |author1= Thomas Driebe |author2= Falk Herwig |publisher= [[Cornell University Library]] |date= September 7, 1998|bibcode= 1998yCat..33390123D }}</ref> and two years later published his finding on evolution of [[convective overshoot]]ing of [[asymptotic giant branch]] stars.<ref>{{cite report |arxiv= astro-ph/0007139 |last=Herwig |first= Falk |title= "The evolution of AGB stars with convective overshoot" |publisher= Cornell University Library |work= [[University of Potsdam]] |date= July 11, 2000}}</ref> In 1999 he and his colleagues described what happens after the star explodes. He used the [[PG 1159 star]] as an example and proved the existence of convective overshooting.<ref>{{cite report |arxiv= astro-ph/9908108 |author1=Falk Herwig |author2=T Blöcker |author3=N Langer |author4= T Driebe |title= "On the formation of hydrogen-deficient post-AGB stars" |publisher= Cornell University Library |date= August 10, 1999}}</ref>

