{{about|the unit of spectral radiance|the unit of time|Flick (time)}}

In [[optical engineering]] and [[telecommunications engineering]], the '''flick''' is a unit of [[spectral radiance]]. One flick corresponds to a  spectral radiance of 1 [[watt]] per [[steradian]] per square [[centimeter]] of surface per [[micrometer]] of span in wavelength (W·sr<sup>−1</sup>·cm<sup>−2</sup>·μm<sup>−1</sup>). This is  equivalent to 10<sup>10</sup> [[watt]]s per [[steradian]] per cubic [[meter]] (W·sr<sup>−1</sup>·m<sup>−3</sup>). In practice, spectral radiance is typically measured in microflicks (10<sup>−6</sup> flicks).<ref>{{cite web|last=Palmer|first=James M.|title=The SI system and SI units for Radiometry and photometry|url=http://www.optics.arizona.edu/palmer/opti400/suppdocs/bkappndx.pdf|access-date=2012-08-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120802170633/http://www.optics.arizona.edu/palmer/opti400/suppdocs/bkappndx.pdf|archive-date=2012-08-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> One microflick is equivalent to 10 kilowatts per steradian per cubic meter (kW·sr<sup>−1</sup>·m<sup>−3</sup>).<ref>{{cite web|last=Rowlett|first=Russ|title=How Many? A Dictionary of Units of Measurement|url=http://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/units/dictF.html#flick|accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref>

==History==
In [[radio astronomy]], the unit '''flik''' was coined by a group at [[Lockheed Corporation|Lockheed]] in [[Palo Alto, California]] as a substitute for the [[SI derived unit]] W cm<sup>−2</sup> sr<sup>−1</sup> µm<sup>−1</sup>, or [[watt]]s divided by [[centimeters]] squared, [[steradian]]s, and [[micrometre|micrometers]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schlessinger|title=Infrared Technology Fundamentals, 2nd ed|date=1994|publisher=[[CRC Press]]|isbn=9780824792596|page=21|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QPBQ5w4X8RkC&lpg=PA21&pg=PA21#v=onepage&q=flik%20unit%20astronomy}}</ref> While it started out used only in Lockheed, many in the radio astronomy field adopted its use.

