{{Infobox person | name = Stephan Swanson | image = | image_size = 225px | caption = Stephan Swanson | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|09|16}} | birth_place = [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa|R.S.A.]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = [[Marine Researcher]] | networth = | spouse = Married to Bonny Swanson with two children | residence = Cape Town, South Africa | website = [http://www.sampla.org Stephan Swanson homepage] | footnotes = }}
'''Stephan Swanson''' came to prominence as a marine researcher when he successfully placed the satellite transmitter on the famous [[Great white shark]] Nicole, the first [[great white shark]] ever to be tracked on a 20,000 kilometer migration from [[South Africa]] to [[Australia]] and back. Due to his ability to handle large marine predators, such as the great white shark, he was contracted as an expedition biologist to travel to [[Guadeloupe]] and place satellite transmitters on the dorsal fins of Great Whites. His historical capture and release of a 5m long, 1800 kilogram great white shark is documented in the [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] Marine Special "Ultimate Shark".
==Scientific Articles== * [http://www.sampla.org/downloads/29.pdf Developing techniques and procedures for large shark telemetry] * [http://www.sampla.org/downloads/17.pdf White shark abundance not a causative factor in shark attack incidence] * [http://www.sampla.org/downloads/16.pdf White shark cage diving - Cause for concern?] * [http://www.sampla.org/downloads/13-14.pdf Transoceanic migrations of a white shark]
==Television appearances== * [https://web.archive.org/web/20080821061845/http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/series/explorer/2589/Overview Ultimate Shark - National Geographic] * [http://channel.nationalgeographic.com/series/wild/3657/Overview Sharkville - National Geographic] * [http://www.pasella.com/episodes/688656.html Pasella - SABC2]
==External links== * [http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/fish/sharks/InNews/monitor2006.html Cape Argus - Project To Monitor The Great White Shark] * [http://www.scienceonline.org/cgi/content/abstract/310/5745/100 Transoceanic Migration, Spatial Dynamics, and Population Linkages of White Sharks] * [http://www.whitesharktrust.co.za/migration.html Shark Nicole to Australia and Back]
