{{Infobox scientist |name = Yoichirō Hirase |image = Yoichiro Hirase 1859-1925.jpg |image_size = |alt = |caption = Yoichirō Hirase |birth_date = {{Birth date|1859|12|04}}<!--from ja wikipedia--> |birth_place = [[Awaji Island]], [[Japan]]<!--from ja wikipedia--> |death_date = {{Death date and age|1925|05|25|1859|12|04}}<!--from ja wikipedia--> |death_place = Japan<!--from ja wikipedia--> |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = |ethnicity = |fields = [[malacology]] |workplaces = |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |footnotes = }}
{{nihongo|'''Yoichirō Hirase'''|平瀬 與一郎|Hirase Yoichirō|December 4, 1859 &ndash; May 25, 1925}} was a Japanese [[malacologist]]. His son, [[Shintarō Hirase]], (1884-1939) was also a malacologist. The majority of [[Shintarō Hirase#Collection|his collection of molluscs]] were destroyed during [[World War II]].<ref name="Clench 1948">[[William J. Clench|Clench W. J.]] (1948). "The Hirase collections of mollusks". ''[[The Nautilus (journal)|The Nautilus]]'' '''62'''(1): [https://archive.org/stream/nautilus62amer#page/34/mode/2up 34]-35.</ref>
[[File:Hirase Conchological Museum.png|left|thumb|The Hirase Conchological Museum in [[Kyoto]] was opened in 1913.<ref>anonymous (1913). "A conchological museum for Japan". ''[[The Nautilus (journal)|The Nautilus]]'' '''27'''(2): [https://archive.org/stream/nautilus27amer#page/n25/mode/2up 13]-14, plate I.</ref>]]
